Sak Yant
 
Buddhist Monks originally engraved Sak Yant designs into warriors seeking protection and strength in battle. Often covering their entire bodies from head to toe in magic symbols like an armor against their enemies. Sak Yant tattoos are done by a Monk using bamboo needles and then blessed with a Buddhist mantra. 

A common practice for Warriors, Fighters, and Monks, it’s truly an honor to be apart of this 2000 year old tradition, not once, but twice. Blessed in 2015 as well, it continues to be a holy, divine, and metaphysical experience. Thank you for your blessing, Kob-Kun-Kap! ขอบคุณ

Bataan Memorial Death March: 26.2 Miles (full marathon) with a 40lb Rucksack 🔥 

During World War II, Tens of thousands of U.S. and Filipino soldiers were forced to become prisoners of war to Japanese forces.
The captive soldiers were forced to march for days on end, approximately 65 miles through the scorching jungles of the Philippines. Thousands died. Those who survived faced the hardships of prisoner war camps and the brutality of their Japanese captors.
The POWs would not see freedom until 1945 when U.S.-Filipino forces recaptured the lost territory. The Bataan Memorial Death March is a commemorative ruckmarch in their honor! 
🇺🇸 🇵🇭

Bushido: The Way of the Warrior. It is a code of conduct and set of values lived by ancient Samurai. Developed in the art of war and lived in a series of virtues, disciplining the mind, and controlling the ego. Deepening my spirit through these ancient philosophies and meditation creates a new level of understanding in the art of war. Sharp and focused, discipling my spirit, not just in combat but in life. 
There is so much correlation between fighting and meditation and how important meditation is in fighting. And the deeper of a meditation you can find yourself in, the more enlightened and open your spirit becomes. Sharpening the mind like a Katana of the Samurai. #Bushido #WayOfTheWarrior #Samurai

Muay Thai, also known as the science of 8 limbs for its use of 2 hands, 2 feet, 2 knees and 2 elbows is the national sport of Thailand. It is one of the main reasons I decided to venture to Thailand in the first place. The sheer passion, honor and respect I have for Muay Thai is profound. From the science of 8 limbs to the Wai Khru Ram Muay, a dance ritual done before every fight in respect to their teacher, their ancestors and the sport. This war dance is a combination of bows, prayers and movements, saluting the Buddha and the sangha monks, to the sounds of a Javanese clarinet that accompany them. The intensity and dedication of the fighters is awe inspiring and motivating nonetheless. Training with @taosmileeee and @dangmuaythai has not only been a privilege but an honor.

My first Jiujitsu tournament. Won both matches. Gold in both divisions, No Gi and Gi with a Submission @newbreedbjj
Jiujitsu, like any other martial art, is a practice not meant to be mastered but a disciplined art where you find continuous growth. There’s always something to be learned both on the mat and within oneself. A continuous journey of respect at every belt level. 
But today’s win was not just about stepping on the mat and walking off successfully, but the hard work that was put in beforehand. The training twice a day, the gym in between multiple classes, the training when you’re tired, the weight cuts, the dieting, the mental studies and preparation and continuously showing up day in and day out. It’s the hard work you put in before the match even begins and that is where the true win lies. 🥇

Thank you to my amazing academy @odysseyjiujitsu my coaches @gregsirico and @danielkwantes (beast mode)
The consistent classes with @amonthedon and @warriors_bjj and all my teammates and rolling partners at Odyssey. You guys are literally the best to train with and learn from and I am honored. I truly value all your experience and expertise in this art! 
To many more medals, banners, and rolling sessions ahead! Congratulations to everyone who stepped on the Mat this weekend. 
Team O!

Losing With Grace and Gratitude:
IBJJF Atlanta Jiujitsu Championships 0-2.
I had a whole caption on what it meant to be tough and resilient (while winning) but it seems like after a tough loss this weekend, being tough and resilient is now even more fitting. It’s not the medals or the wins. 
Being resilient is in the losses and being tough is in the Consistently. Showing. Up. 👏🏼
And that’s both on the mats, and in life. From athletics to your relationships to your career. Showing up and keeping at it! And when you get knocked the F’ down, you dust yourself off and stand right the F’ back up! 
Continually, continuously, challenging yourself in this life. It’s pushing hard to make weight, showing up for training (sometimes twice a day), it’s putting in the work and still accepting defeat when you gave it everything you got.

Training HARD for this competition was a win, stepping on the mat and competing was a win, fighting with a bruised rib was a win, and losing with grace IS A Win! 
So I am honored to Lose with Grace and Gratitude this weekend. Especially to two of my toughest opponents. It was honor to compete with you guys! @christopher_bogdanski_shore and Ryan. (Killer judo slam Chris - Well played.) 

Truly truly Honored to be apart of Team Odyssey @odysseyjiujitsu and having some of the best coaches an athlete could ask for. @gregsirico @warriors_bjj 
@danielkwantes @amonthedon @catpapijj 

Having you all in my corner makes me the Warrior I am! ⚔️ 
Congrats to every one of my teammates who competed this weekend. Hands down you guys are the best damn teammates! 🫶🏼

Here’s to Losing With Grace and Gratitude! 

Till Next Season 🔥

One Year Alcohol Free! It was never about being “Sober” but striving to be the best version of myself. Pushing a little more each day to become stronger, sharper, and healthier. Learning to sit with my emotions than mask them and recognizing that there are things that no longer serve my full potential. I always thought that with not drinking I would be missing out…. but the truth is, I missed out on so much more when I choose drinking over who I truly want to be. This is my life and I am in control….Cheers to that! Solid!
